Task 1: Boot Tails OS and Configure Tor
Subtask 1.1: Download and Prepare Tails OS
First, we'll download Tails OS and prepare it for use on our Linux machine.

# Create a working directory for Tails
mkdir ~/tails-lab
cd ~/tails-lab

# Download Tails ISO (latest stable version)
wget https://download.tails.net/tails/stable/tails-amd64-5.19.1/tails-amd64-5.19.1.img

# Verify the download integrity
wget https://download.tails.net/tails/stable/tails-amd64-5.19.1/tails-amd64-5.19.1.img.sig

# Install required packages for verification
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y gnupg2 qemu-kvm qemu-utils virt-manager
Subtask 1.2: Set Up Virtual Environment for Tails
Since we're working on a single Linux machine, we'll use QEMU to run Tails in a virtual environment.

# Create a virtual disk for persistent storage (optional)
qemu-img create -f qcow2 ~/tails-lab/tails-persistent.qcow2 8G

# Create a script to launch Tails
cat > ~/tails-lab/launch-tails.sh << 'EOF'
#!/bin/bash
qemu-system-x86_64 \
    -m 2048 \
    -enable-kvm \
    -cdrom ~/tails-lab/tails-amd64-5.19.1.img \
    -boot d \
    -netdev user,id=net0 \
    -device e1000,netdev=net0 \
    -display gtk \
    -usb \
    -device usb-tablet
EOF

# Make the script executable
chmod +x ~/tails-lab/launch-tails.sh
